    thinking: "**Defining User Need**\n\nI\'m now focused on clarifying user needs for the \"Collection Territory Intelligence System.\" It appears the user\'s prompt is in Indonesian, which adds a layer to understanding their objectives and the system\'s role in helping them. This is the new priority.\n\n\n**Clarifying System Objectives**\n\nI\'ve made progress defining the system\'s objectives. It\'s now clear that the user wants a system to determine the best collectors for new customers. The primary goals are to reduce unserved areas, optimize collector routes, minimize customer complaints from infrequent visits, and provide data-driven recommendations. I\'m also now building a React + TypeScript web application, for the user, in a web application based on this.\n\n\n\n**Interpreting User Intent**\n\nI\'m now determining if the user wants a full web application or just an API. The prompt seems designed for an LLM that returns JSON, but I\'m building a web app. I\'m checking my system prompt to confirm I must build exactly what\'s requested, avoiding extra features. I will ask for clarification if needed.\n\n\n**Designing Application Structure**\n\nI\'m now designing the application structure. After re-reading the prompt, it\'s clear the user provided a complete system specification. I\'ve decided to create an interactive React web application named \"Collection Territory Intelligence System\" to provide the specified functionality. Users can input customer data and collector profiles. I\'ll pre-populate it with realistic Indonesian mock data.\n\n\n**Analyzing Data Parameters**\n\nI\'m now focusing on data parameters. I\'ll need addresses, collector info, activities, transactions, and coordinates \342\200\223 potentially leveraging Jakarta or Bali geolocation data, which is an exciting angle, and I\'ll include preloaded samples.\n\nI must now run the analysis engine, specifically using Haversine distance, recency weights, and area divisions, with subscores based on proximity, activity frequency, transaction amount, activity consistency, and workload. I will be sure to combine subscores with weights.\n\n\n**Calculating Scoring and Confidence**\n\nI\'m now implementing the scoring and confidence calculations. The formula is finalized, scores will be rounded to integers from 0-100. I\'m also working on determining confidence levels (HIGH, MEDIUM, LOW) based on activity thresholds, recency, and coefficient of variation. Edge cases like cold starts and ties are also being addressed. I\'m focusing on ensuring accurate JSON output that adheres strictly to the specified schema.\n\n\n**Designing Output Options**\n\nI\'ve realized the need for an explicit JSON output feature for easy copying or previewing. This will be a key part of the UI. I\'m verifying the input/output method, and I\'m leaning toward a client-side React app for safety and responsiveness. The UI will have custom visual elements, maps, data tables, and simulation panels. I\'m also now considering API route writing and backend integration options, depending on the need, and skill set, as it is a nice option. I see the skills, such as shadcn-ui, as helpful for this.\n\n\n**Considering Database Connectivity**\n\nI\'m now considering database connectivity, specifically addressing the MySQL mention in the prompt. While our current database setup doesn\'t include MySQL (we use Cloud SQL with PostgreSQL), I\'m interpreting this as a potential user data format. Therefore, I will design the app with functionality to handle CSV or JSON data uploads, enabling users to import data that might have originated from a MySQL database, so it won\'t be a blocker, and data can be loaded.\n\n\n**Evaluating Database Needs**\n\nI\'m now evaluating the database needs. Since there\'s no actual MySQL instance, I\'ll allow users to upload data as JSON, CSV, or even MySQL insert statements for flexibility. I\'m also considering integrating a Gemini API helper on the server side to generate custom Indonesian summaries and risk analyses based on the calculations.\n\n\n"
