  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Defining Engine Implementation**\n\nOkay, I\'m now focusing on how to construct the calculator and analysis engine within `/src/engine.ts`. My key considerations right now are accurately calculating distances with the Haversine formula. I also need to make sure the implementation allows for segmenting areas into zones: inner (under 1km), secondary (1-3km), and outer (beyond 3km).\n\n\n**Calculating Recency and CV**\n\nI\'ve been calculating recency weights using 90- and 180-day intervals relative to a reference date. Currently, I\'m focusing on weekly activity bin counts and the Coefficient of Variation (CV). The calculation of week numbers seems robust and accurate, using 7-day increments from the start date. Now, I need to ensure that weeks with zero visits are also counted in the binning process.\n\n\n**Refining Week Calculation**\n\nI\'ve made a breakthrough with the weekly activity binning! Instead of only counting weeks with activity, I\'m now calculating the total number of weeks in the analysis period, which runs from `minActivityTime` to `maxActivityTime`. This allows for a more accurate and fairer representation of the territory. I can now initialize an array with zeros for each collector, and increment the bin for each activity within the defined radius. This means even weeks with no visits are correctly counted as zero, which accurately models real-world scenarios. It increases standard deviation and lowers the consistency score.\nNow I\'m focusing on the Coefficient of Variation (CV) calculation, and how to define `consistency_score`.\n\n\n**Clamping Consistency Score**\n\nOkay, so I realized the calculation for `consistency_score` might yield negative values if CV is high. I\'ve implemented clamping to ensure the score always stays between 0 and 100, which is `Math.max(0, Math.min(100, 100 - (CV * 100)))`. I\'m now implementing these precise calculations directly into `/src/engine.ts`. I\'m revisiting the components and weights, starting with proximity to the operational area, which is 35% of the score. I\'m focusing on the weighted distance calculation and normalization relative to all analyzed collectors.\n\n\n**Calculating Frequency and Transactions**\n\nI\'m now diving into the frequency and transaction components of the score, which are 25% and 15% respectively. The weighted frequency, calculated as the sum of recency-weighted activities within 3 km, is being implemented with a normalization step using `frekuensi_score = 100 * (F_weighted / F_weighted_max)`. I\'ve added a check for zero maximum activity to prevent division by zero, setting the score to zero in such cases. I\'m taking a similar approach for the transaction component, using recency-weighted transaction amounts within 3 km, and normalizing using `transaksi_score = 100 * (T_weighted / T_weighted_max)`, again handling the zero maximum value.\n\n\n**Finalizing Collector Scoring**\n\nNow, I\'m integrating the final component: Collector workload, which makes up 10% of the score. I\'m calculating `beban_score` as `100 * (1 - active_customers / active_customers_max)`, where the maximum active customers are taken from all compared collectors. I\'ve added a check for the case when `active_customers_max` equals zero, in which case `beban_score` becomes 100. Finally, I\'ve combined all the components with their weights to calculate the overall score, and rounded it to the nearest integer. I\'ve also worked on defining the confidence levels, and have implemented logic to categorize them as High or Medium, based on activity frequency and consistency.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I will create `/src/engine.ts` which implements the complete, deterministic mathematical and analysis engine for the Collection Territory Intelligence System. It calculates distances, segments the space, applies recency weights, counts weekly visits, computes the coefficient of variation (CV) for consistency, weighs workloads, applies tie-breakers, checks edge cases, and constructs the report schema. This engine will work on both the server and client."
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 10
      nanos: 103026612
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
